\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
1.
 Purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The purpose of this policy is to establish the mandatory requirements for the secure configuration,
 hardening,
 and continuous monitoring of all Elko County Information Operations (ECIO) technology assets.
 This policy enforces the principle of least functionality to minimize the organizational attack surface and ensure the confidentiality,
 integrity,
 and availability of County systems,
 with specific emphasis on environments processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
2.
 Scope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy applies to all ECIO personnel,
 contractors,
 and third-party vendors.
 The scope encompasses all physical and virtual hardware,
 operating systems,
 network infrastructure,
 software applications,
 and cloud environments owned,
 leased,
 or managed by Elko County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
3.
 Roles and Responsibilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT Director
\series default
:
 Shall serve as the final approval authority for all enterprise baseline configuration standards,
 formal risk acceptance,
 and policy exceptions documented in the System Security Plan (SSP).
 Shall serve as the Configuration Control Authority (CCA) and Local Agency Security Officer (LASO) for all configuration decisions affecting CJI systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Assistant IT Director
\series default
:
 Shall define the secure configuration benchmarks based on mandatory frameworks,
 audit baseline compliance across all operational domains,
 mandate remediation for non-compliant assets,
 and maintain the Configuration Management Database (CMDB) as the authoritative record of approved configuration baselines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Systems Administrator
\series default
:
 Shall engineer,
 apply,
 and maintain approved configuration baselines on all assigned server and endpoint computing assets prior to production deployment and throughout the asset lifecycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Network Administrator
\series default
:
 Shall engineer,
 apply,
 and maintain approved configuration baselines on all assigned network infrastructure,
 boundary protection,
 and communication assets prior to production deployment and throughout the asset lifecycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
4.
 Compliance and Exceptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Violations of this policy shall result in the immediate isolation of the non-compliant asset from the production network and may subject the responsible personnel to disciplinary action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Any deviation from an approved configuration baseline must be submitted via a formal Exception Request.
 The request shall include a documented technical justification,
 compensating controls,
 and a defined expiration date.
 Exceptions are invalid unless formally approved in writing by both the Assistant IT Director and the IT Director.
 For exceptions affecting systems that process,
 store,
 or transmit Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 written approval from the CJIS Systems Officer (CSO) shall be obtained prior to implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Unauthorized systems discovered operating without an approved baseline shall be treated as Shadow IT.
 In such events,
 Incident Response isolation protocols shall trigger automatically,
 and asset handling shall default to the enforcement mechanisms defined in ECIO 
