\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Baseline Configuration Establishment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
ECIO shall establish,
 document,
 and maintain secure configuration baselines for all information systems.
 Baselines must be strictly derived from Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) Security Technical Implementation Guides (STIGs).
 Where an applicable DISA STIG does not exist for a specific system class,
 the Center for Internet Security (CIS) Benchmark at Level 2 or higher shall serve as the mandatory fallback baseline standard.
 The absence of an applicable STIG and the use of the CIS fallback shall be documented in the SSP.
 The Assistant IT Director shall review and update these baselines at least annually or upon the introduction of a new system architecture to ensure alignment with the latest releases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To support rollback capabilities,
 ECIO shall retain at least one (1) prior approved version of the baseline configuration for each system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Network Topological Drawing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
ECIO shall develop,
 document,
 and maintain under configuration control a current and complete topological drawing depicting the interconnectivity of the County network to criminal justice information systems and services.
 The Assistant IT Director shall review and update this drawing at least annually,
 upon security-relevant system changes,
 and when network components are installed or upgraded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Principle of Least Functionality and System Hardening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information systems shall be configured to provide only essential capabilities.
 Services,
 daemons,
 ports,
 protocols,
 and applications not explicitly justified in the approved System Security Plan (SSP) and documented within the Configuration Management Database (CMDB) baseline shall be disabled or removed prior to production deployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Systems in production at the effective date of this policy shall be assessed against the applicable baseline within ninety (90) days of the effective date.
 Non-compliant systems shall be remediated or formally excepted under Section 4 within one hundred eighty (180) days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Default Account and Credential Hardening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All default,
 guest,
 and built-in vendor accounts shall be disabled,
 renamed,
 or strictly restricted before an asset is joined to the production network.
 Default authentication credentials (e.g.,
 passwords,
 SNMP strings,
 SSH keys) shall be changed to meet current enterprise cryptographic and complexity standards prior to deployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Configuration Change Control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Modifications to established configuration baselines shall not occur outside of the formal ITIL Change Management process,
 in accordance with ECIO 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Change Management Policy).
 System and Network Administrators must submit a Request for Change (RFC) and receive Configuration Control Authority (CCA) approval prior to altering configuration settings on production systems.
 Emergency changes shall follow the emergency change procedure and shall follow the emergency change procedure and complete catch-up documentation and CCA review in accordance with the timelines established in 
\series bold
Policy 
